How many of you are familiar with these concepts?
Marginal Land vs. Arable Land
Many people ask why not use the land to grow food for humans?" Because you can't.
-Around 30% of land on the earth is agricultural land (useable for the purpose of making food, the rest is junk).
-Take 66% of that 30% of land. That is "marginal land."
- Marginal land is not suitable for growing crops due to soil quality or not enough water etc. So what can you do with it?
-You can have cows graze on the cellulose on this land (again, this land is not suitable for growing edible crops), and turn that cellulose into protein and various nutrients humans need.

Ruminant Upcycling
-33% of that agricultural land mentioned above can be used for crops. (Nice.) This is called "arable land."
-Though, for every 100lbs of human food produced from crops on this land, roughly 37 lbs of inedible plant byproduct is produced.
-Cows can eat this inedible plant matter and turn it into protein.
-Worthless cellulose + Cow = Human Food

Biogenic Carbon Cycle in a nutshell:
-Methane has stronger warming potential than CO2 so cow burp is bad, right? Well...
-Plants capture carbon from the atmosphere via photosynthesis
-Cows eat the plant, take the carbon.
-Cows burp out the carbon in the form of methane (remember methane is CH4 - Carbon, 4 Hydrogens)
-12 yeas later, Methane is broken down back into carbon dioxide via hydroxyl oxidation.
*These carbon molecules are the same molecules that were in the plant the Cow ate. It's a natural cycle.
(By the way, the carbon dioxide added to the environment by burning fossil fuels (not part of any life cycle) stays in the atmosphere for 200 „Äú 1000 years)

Vox is lying to you.

1. Cattle production is carbon neutral. They do not emit any more carbon dioxide or methane than they take in through grass and other fodder.

2. Cattle are not as polluting as fossil fuels. Fossil fuels are dug up from the ground and then burned and go into the atmosphere. It is entirely NEW green house gasses that were previous sequestered deep underground. Cattle does not produce NEW gasses. It converts organic material into meat and waste. Nothing is new. That waste and gasses are taken up by plants and bacteria. That makes it a carbon neutral system.

3. Cattle emissions are ground level emissions. They are quickly taken up by plants and bacteria. How else could they grow except by taking up ground level CO2 and other emissions?

4. Much cattle production in the US doesn't require the clearing of forests. They graze in open areas that already exist. Even if areas are cleared this is no different than for any field crop. Perhaps some fruit and nut crops result in some carbon sequestration but that is nothing compared to the forests that existed there before.

There are many reasons to not eat meat. Not the least of which is that it is often cruel and wasteful. However, this video falls under the "False Consciousness" rule. They are trying to convince you that it's really cattle that is causing climate change and not the fossil fuel industry.

Make no mistake. The primary threat to our environment comes from fossil fuels and not cows.

We could increase cattle production 10 times what it is now on existing grazing and there would be no increase in atmospheric CO2 or methane so long cows would be consuming grass and other fodder as they always have.

Finally, much cattle production happens in areas where agriculture is not suitable. The notion that cattle is displacing other types of farms in these areas is untrue. Much of the Southwest is given to cattle because they can graze but have little impact on the other animals in the region. This is absolutely opposite of field crops which require the bulldozing of fields and the slaughter of every animal and plant in that area to make room for one single field crop (like corn, or soybeans). Then that field is cleansed every year with a new slaughter to make room for the next crop and this includes the use of pesticides and herbicides (which aren't used in cattle industry). In this sense, cattle production is much less cruel than soybean or wheat production. Not only do the cattle coexist with many other animals but also when you eat a hamburger you've only killed one animal. Eat a soyburger and you've killed hundreds.

Actually, there is a misunderstanding about contribution of beef in green house emissions specific to Indian context. The statement "beef industry causes global warming" is only true in West, where there is seperate industrial livestock farming for meat. Those breed are fast-growing high weight-gaining category specially grown for meat. They are not much useful for dairy industry, which has other type of breeds. In India, there is no industrial livestock farming for beef. Almost all methane emissions in India is from cattle grown for milk. Our dairy farmers and farms give them for slaughter only once they run dry (no more able to produce milk) which forms major part of beef supply in India. For small farmers, this is the money they use to buy next cow. In fact, beef consumption in India helps reduce methane emission, because they remove such cattle from population, which otherwise will continue to emit it. Point is, dairy farms are major culprits. If anybody genuinely cares about this issue, the best way is reverse "White revolution" and promote reduction milk consumption.

It really depends on where and how grazing animals would be good for the environment. If land must be cleared, aka forests (looking at Brazil here), its a net negative. However if it is to put back nutrients into depleted soil then its great. However most ranching is done for profit and not to restock soil due to "inefficient" land usage (far more land needs to be used if cattle are to graze rather then feed on fodder and grain). As a whole if land in areas where soils are depleted or is subject to desertification then it would help the environment locally. This is due to the land being already depleted you still need to provide feed otherwise the grazing animals will starve. There was a good TED talk about this a number of years ago if you want to search for it.

You need to adjust the chart based upon viable protein content and include water consumption. A gallon of water for a single almond. 5 gallons for a walnut. Large mono-cultures eventually ruin the soil. You really can't have plants without animals/insects.
Although I agree that the methane cows burp is significant, this is being worked on and cows produce a lot more beneficial products than just beef and methane. Actually, there is a misunderstanding about contribution of beef in green house emissions specific to Indian context. The statement "beef industry causes global warming" is only true in West, where there is seperate industrial livestock farming for meat. Those breed are fast-growing high weight-gaining category specially grown for meat. They are not much useful for dairy industry, which has other type of breeds. In India, there is no industrial livestock farming for beef. Almost all methane emissions in India is from cattle grown for milk. Our dairy farmers and farms give them for slaughter only once they run dry (no more able to produce milk) which forms major part of beef supply in India. For small farmers, this is the money they use to buy next cow. In fact, beef consumption in India helps reduce methane emission, because they remove such cattle from population, which otherwise will continue to emit it. Point is, dairy farms are major culprits. If anybody genuinely cares about this issue, the best way is reverse "White revolution" and promote reduction milk consumption.

This video would be great if it weren't for one fatal flaw. Methane production from cows DOES NOT CONTRIBUTE TO GLOBAL WARMING. Cows are part of a natural carbon cycle. They eat grass/grain, made of carbon which was fixed from CO2 in the atmosphere. They eat the grass and digest it. They then emit CO2 and methane, carbon which was already located in the grass and is now in the air again to be fixed by plants. It is completely separate from fossil fuel carbon, which is introduction CO2 into the air which had been trapped in rocks for millions of years. The number of cows in the United States has not been increasing, in fact it has been decreasing in the past two decades due to genetics and better management practice. This means that beef/dairy production has actually contributed to global cooling! Also, looking at these systems from a global standpoint doesn't make sense. Beef you and I eat comes from America, where we literally have millions of acres of ground in the western part of the United States which is too poor to grow crops on but is only adequate for ruminant use (animals which turn stuff we cannot eat, such as grass, into extremely nutritious foods). This one misconception about GHG emissions alone (due to kg CO2 equivalents which are not a good way to compare livestock to other industries) is creating extremely dangerous misconceptions against farmers/ranchers and their products.

@Sie, Evan Setiawan rightfully so! There is a lot of misinformation out there. CO2eq is useful for a lot of things, but it grossly miscalculates impact from ruminant animals (such as ovine and bovine species) by not considering the fact they're a part of a natural cycle meanwhile fossil fuels and concrete production are not. If you want to learn more look up Dr. Frank Mitloehner, a climate scientist specifically involved in researching animal agricultural impact at UC Davis. He has a lot of great videos that can give a lot more information. He's also on Twitter!

According to Beef Market Central, the US consumes about 21% of the world's beef. China is next at 14% (but with ~5x the population), followed closely by Brazil and the EU, both at around 13% (Brazil is ~50% of EU population). Per capita, the ratings change a bit between sources, because different organizations use different standards to measure consumption, but the generally agreed trend is that the highest per capita consumers are North and South Americans (notably US, Brazil, Uruguay, Argentina, Chile, and Canada) along with Australia, Kazakhstan, Hong Kong, and Israel.

Sie, Evan Setiawan As long as the number of rumenants stays on the current level, their contribution is overall positive since it leads to CO2 sequestration (which interestingly enough can't be achieved with planting trees for example). We do however want to avoid global warming from further CO2 emission since that eventually will lead to frozen methane being released from the ground, accelerating the CO2 damage. So overall, methane release and resorption works in a cycle, CO2 release however is problematic since it just adds up and stays in the atmosphere
Does that mean methane absorption rate 10 years later is same as methane release rate now? Or the absorption rate is constant and we have to keep release rate below absorption rate?

@Sie, Evan Setiawan The calculations still treat the impact of methane as if it stays in the atmosphere indefinitely like CO2, whereas it actually has about a 10 year lifecycle, returning back to the soil. It also assumes that cattle is fed anything other than grass, which certainly is problematic and we shouldn't do. It would be more effective for the environment to advocate against factory farming practices as opposed to advocating against beef altogether since the restoration and maintenance of natural grasslands with the help of rumenants contributes to carbon dioxide sequestration and replenishment of valuable top soil.

You could do sequel to episode about crops that require the most water. We have many places in the world that have had or are facing zero days. In Australia, we have a '"water buyback" scheme for the Murray-Darling Basin (Australia's food bowl. Which stretches from Queensland through NSW all the way to Victoria). It was meant to be a way of balancing the use of water by limiting the volume of water that farmers could extract from the river. The government 'buys back' water entitlements from growers, thereby reducing the amount of water taken from the river.

Now you don't need to be a farmer to own water entitlements, in fact the Chinese and the US are the biggest investors in our water entitlements. The government was caught paying $80 million of tax payers money to company that is registered to the Cayman Islands.

Last year during our summer (which is very dry) water stopped flowing in the rivers causing large blue-green algae blooms which starved oxygen to all the fish. Millions of fish were killed and seen floating in the river. While there was a drought and lot of finger pointing on to blame, what we need to remember is that the basin can only support so much. Why are we growing things like cotton, chestnuts and rice? Things that require so much water. We should be growing things that suit our climate. This is why a follow up video to this one but about water usage I think is important for people to know.

This is talking about factory farming not well raised cows! A very important distinction. When cows have a diet of pasture grasses instead of corn and grain, they produce far less methane. They also have the opportunity to support grass root growth through grazing which sequesters carbon. I agree that humans should eat less beef, but I also think they should eat better beef. Please consider supporting local organic cattle farmers. There are people out there doing it right, and eating beef can be a positive thing to support them and the environment. Another thing to think about is the fertilizer cows can provide in a positive farm system. If we hope to move away from chemical fertilizers which contaminate land, water, and wildlife we need to pursue sustainable fertilizers. Cattle can contribute to this system with their manure. Overall this issue is incredibly complicated but the most important thing to realize is not all cattle are raised equally (both environmentally and ethically) and it‚Äôs possible to be an active consumer and choose good beef!

A kilogram of beef for example only comprises about 4 individual steaks, whereas a kilo of coffee beans can stretch to make around 100 cups of coffee. Even though coffee or cocoa might contribute about a quarter of the greenhouse emissions as beef per unit mass, we typically consume (and thus produce) these foods in quantities much lower than products like meat or fruit or grains, and so their relative impact is actually less than this in practice. The same can be said of foods like olive oil or nuts, which are calorie-dense. So enjoy your morning brew!

@Kay'la Sen TLDR: People add meat back into their diets too quickly, and it makes them sick because they have to build the correct enzymes back up. While I cannot know for certain, I do not think you are actually allergic to beef. I'm a vegetarian, I have been since I was three years old, so I haven't eaten any meat or fish for a solid amount of time. And of course, because of this, my body doesn't produce enough enzymes and stuff to actually process and digest meat. Thus if I tried eating a hamburger right now, I'd end up extremely sick. However, there have been a number of vegetarians and vegans who at one point stop being vegetarian/vegan. They also end up being sick if they don't GRADUALLY add meat back into their diet. Your body, unless you are truly allergic, still has those enzymes to digest meat, just not enough of them by a long shot, and thus you'll end up making yourself sick. So people trying to get back into eating meat, have to do it very gradually, its a process because you are basically teaching your body how to digest meat again. Of course, I can't know if you are truly allergic or not, nor are you required to actually go and eat meat again, but I've seen enough people think they are allergic to meat when they really are just adding it into their diet too quickly.

Check: if r2a=0.5*r2=8.85/2=4.425, then A2/A1=4.425^2=19.6. This is close enough to 21 that given human error in measurements, theory #1 stands as a definite maybe.

It‚Äôs accurate. The green circle should occupy 1/21 times the area of the yellow circle. This means that it‚Äôs diameter should be 1/(21^0.5) times the diameter of the yellow circle, which is roughly 1/4.5 . The diameter of the yellow circle is 4.5 times the diameter of the green circle.

The real solution (in my opinion) to the beef problem is not to say ‚ÄòDon‚Äôt eat it‚Äô, because although some of us try to reduce our intake or even eliminate it completely, there are other people that are not willing to do it and they have their right to do it, so the wheel keeps turning in favor of big corporations. If you want some information and you care about our soils you can find interesting some of the following topics/examples: regenerative agriculture, the savory institute, Rodale institue or just permaculture. Also great examples are Joel Salatin, Joyce Farms, Charles Massy or Stoney Creek Farm. Maybe you have a farm near where you live and you can take action. Besides cattle, new sources of methane have been adding to the problem. They are due to global warming. One is methane deposits in the seafloor that are being released. Also, as arctic ice melts in Siberia, Canada, and Greenland methane deposits from the permafrost underneath is being released. Finally, in the US, the rise of fracking has resulted in the fracking process leaking lots of methane into the atmosphere. NASA has tracked a huge rise in methane emissions from what's called the Permian Basin, which is the land in the midwest US where fracking is the most prevalent. Methane is probably a big contributor to the reason why global warming seems to be happening faster than predicted. If you just use CO2 in the predictions and leave out methane, you will get less warming which takes longer to reach tipping point levels. But add in the methane, which doesn't last as long but makes the temperature rise more quickly, and you have a real problem that is growing faster than expected.

What is the distinction between "Milk", "Cheese", and "Beef (Dairy)"?

‚Ä¢ Cheese gets a separate bar because on top of milk's emissions, it makes more from processing it into cheese. ‚Ä¢ The milk bar is milk from non-cow sources (which is actually rare outside of North America), so it's low. ‚Ä¢ Cow-milk, which is a mainly western thing, requires cows plus processing, which is why it's so high. ‚Ä¢ Beef also requires cows, but also requires a lot of extra processing which further increases its emissions. ‚Ä¢ One cow can produce milk repeatedly, but it can produce beef only once, hence beef is so much higher than milk.

What this video does not examine further is how the farming practices largely influence overall emissions. Cows, while big producers of methane, have the incredible ability to aid in carbon SEQUESTRATION through the fertility their manure provides to land. Since the demand of beef is so high and people eat so much of it (just eat less), farmers have been pressured to raising beef the most profitable way, typically not through responsible practices. But by no means are cows the problem, we are. Instead cows could actually be part of the solution through responsible holistic management like intensive rotational grazing and composting on site. The reality of crops and beef being raised separately disrupts the possible cycle of fertility that could actually aid in soil building, and offset the methane emissions a herd produced.

Even with all the invested resource use (immense amount of water not only for the cattle but for the feed that feeds them when they‚Äôre not grazing) wouldn‚Äôt truly be terrible emissions if it went towards the ecological use of cattle to build topsoil, like the great herds of bison, wildebeest, or other ruminant animals that have grazed grasslands and savannas for millenia

Actually, there is a misunderstanding about contribution of beef in green house emissions specific to Indian context. The statement "beef industry causes global warming" is only true in West, where there is seperate industrial livestock farming for meat. Those breed are fast-growing high weight-gaining category specially grown for meat. They are not much useful for dairy industry, which has other type of breeds. In India, there is no industrial livestock farming for beef. Almost all methane emissions in India is from cattle grown for milk. Our dairy farmers and farms give them for slaughter only once they run dry (no more able to produce milk) which forms major part of beef supply in India. For small farmers, this is the money they use to buy next cow. In fact, beef consumption in India helps reduce methane emission, because they remove such cattle from population, which otherwise will continue to emit it. Point is, dairy farms are major culprits. If anybody genuinely cares about this issue, the best way is reverse "White revolution" and promote reduction milk consumption.

What‚Äôs the difference between ‚ÄúBeef (Dairy)‚Äù, ‚ÄúBeef,‚Äù ‚ÄúDairy,‚Äù and ‚ÄúCheese‚Äù?

‚Ä¢ Cheese causes extra emissions due to the processing required to turn milk into cheese. ‚Ä¢ Milk is non-cow sources which is the most common source outside of western countries, and it's low. ‚Ä¢ Cow-milk requires cows, so it's higher than non-cow milk. ‚Ä¢ Beef requires extra processing on top of the base emissions from cows. ‚Ä¢ One cow can produce milk repeatedly, but it can produce beef only once, hence beef is so much higher than milk.

Beef (Dairy) is the dairy cows used for meat in later life, the farming process is less intense due to differing farming methods. It‚Äôs industrial beef farming which is the big baddy and highlights that one of the key things that needs to done is souring meat more consciously.
